{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473524"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:09:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:09:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2482"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2482"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.66,0.03,0.1,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2482"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77092"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2482"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2482"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62598"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"},{"type":"tags","id":"1108"},{"type":"tags","id":"1150"},{"type":"tags","id":"1961"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2163"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3349"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3860"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77092"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-month history of bizarre behaviour and social withdrawal. She has spent most of this time in her bedroom working on an \u0022important project\u0022. She reports that television advertisements have been instructing her to submit designs for a new generation of nuclear-powered submarine. She believes foreign spies have implanted listening devices throughout her house, except her bedroom. She reports hearing these spies plotting against her downstairs. She has no significant medical or psychiatric history and takes no regular medications. Her parents report no known recreational drug use or family history of psychiatric illness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears dishevelled and tired. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her BMI is 22kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Mental state examination reveals organised thought form with grandiose and persecutory delusions. She denies suicidal or homicidal ideation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate antipsychotic medication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haloperidol","Aripiprazole","Zuclopenthixol","Clozapine","Sodium valproate"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with first episode psychosis (FEP), characterised by delusions, hallucinations, and social withdrawal. After a brief period of observation and assessment (24-48 hours), pharmacotherapy with a second-generation antipsychotic is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAripiprazole\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice as it is a second-generation antipsychotic with better tolerability compared to first-generation agents. Other suitable options might include amisulpride, quetiapine, risperidone, or ziprasidone. While olanzapine is effective, its significant metabolic side effects often limit its use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ezuclopenthixol\u003C/strong\u003E are first-generation antipsychotics with higher rates of extrapyramidal side effects, hyperprolactinaemia, and QTc prolongation. They are not preferred for first-line treatment of FEP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClozapine\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for treatment-resistant psychosis after failure of two other antipsychotics. While highly effective, it requires intensive monitoring due to serious potential side effects including agranulocytosis, myocarditis, and paralytic ileus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium valproate\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used as a mood stabiliser. While it may occasionally be added to antipsychotic therapy if there are significant affective symptoms, it is not first-line treatment for psychosis. It should be used with extreme caution in women of childbearing age due to significant teratogenic risks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Second-generation antipsychotics are first-line treatment for first episode psychosis in young people","A period of observation and assessment (24-48 hours) should precede pharmacotherapy in first episode psychosis","Clozapine is reserved for treatment-resistant psychosis after failure of two antipsychotic trials"],"references":["Early Psychosis Guidelines Writing Group. Australian Clinical Guidelines for Early Psychosis, 2nd edition: A Brief Summary for Practitioners. In: Orygen Youth Health, Melbourne [online]. 2016. Available at: https://www.orygen.org.au/Campus/Expert-Network/Resources/Free/Clinical-Practice/Australian-Clinical-Guidelines-for-Early-Psychosis/Australian-Clinical-Guidelines-for-Early-Psychosis.aspx?ext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62598"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2482"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62598"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T09:00:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T09:00:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"it